                                "start": 0,
                                "stop": 9.168,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Justice Scalia has our opinion this morning in Case 14-86, EEOC v. Abercrombie \u0026 Fitch."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 9.168,
                        "stop": 301.272,
                        "byte_start": 0,
                        "byte_stop": 0,
                        "speaker": {
                            "ID": 15049,
                            "name": "Antonin Scalia",
                            "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/people\/antonin_scalia",
                            "last_name": "Scalia",
                            "roles": [
                                {
                                    "id": 2693,
                                    "type": "scotus_justice",
                                    "date_start": 528094800,
                                    "date_end": 0,
                                    "appointing_president": "Ronald Reagan",
                                    "role_title": "Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "institution_name": "Supreme Court of the United States",
                                    "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/preson_role\/scotus_justice\/2693"
                                }
                            ],
                            "thumbnail": {
                                "id": 32678,
                                "mime": "image\/png",
                                "size": 58944,
                                "href": "https:\/\/api.oyez.org\/sites\/default\/files\/antonin_scalia_0.png"
                            },
                            "length_of_service": 10699,
                            "identifier": "antonin_scalia"
                        },
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 9.168,
                                "stop": 14.455,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "This is really easy."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 14.455,
                                "stop": 19.931,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The case is here on writ of certiorari to the United States Court of Appeals for the Tenth Circuit."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 19.931,
                                "stop": 32.69,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 prohibits employers from failing to hire an employee because of the employee\u0027s religious practice."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 32.69,
                                "stop": 47.333,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "This case requires us to determine whether an employer must have actual knowledge of a prospective employee\u0027s need for an accommodation -- for an accommodation to the religious practice in order to violate this provision."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 47.333,
                                "stop": 57.51,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Samantha Elauf is a practicing Muslim, who in accordance with her understanding of her religious obligations, wears a headscarf."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 57.51,
                                "stop": 64.753,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "She sought a position as a retail employee with respondent Abercrombie \u0026 Fitch Stores."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 64.753,
                                "stop": 81.458,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Abercrombie \u0026 Fitch maintains a dress policy, what it calls a dress policy, for all retail employees, which, among other things, prohibits floor employees from wearing \u201ccaps.\u201d"
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 81.458,
                                "stop": 92.074,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "An Abercrombie \u0026 Fitch manager determined that the corporation\u0027s dress policy did not permit Elauf to wear her headscarf while on duty."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 92.074,
                                "stop": 108.181,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Though there is some dispute about the degree of certainty Abercrombie\u0027s employees had regarding the religious nature of Elauf\u0027s practice, they at least suspected that she wore the headscarf for a religious reason."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 108.181,
                                "stop": 117.257,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Abercrombie acknowledges that it did not hire Elauf because of noncompliance with the store\u0027s dress policy."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 117.257,
                                "stop": 130.128,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, petitioner here, sued on Elauf\u0027s behalf and the District Court granted the EEOC summary judgment on Abercrombie\u0027s liability."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 130.128,
                                "stop": 132.379,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The Tenth Circuit reversed."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 132.379,
                                "stop": 149.282,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The Tenth Circuit concluded that when an employee\u0027s religious obligation requires an accommodation from an employer, the employer cannot be liable under Title VII until the employee provides actual notice of the need for an accommodation."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 149.282,
                                "stop": 160.337,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Since the Tenth Circuit concluded that Elauf did not provide this actual notice, it granted summary judgment instead to Abercrombie."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 160.337,
                                "stop": 163.337,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "We reverse the Tenth Circuit\u0027s judgment."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 163.337,
                                "stop": 168.763,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The Tenth Circuit\u0027s analysis confuses two concepts: knowledge and motive."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 168.763,
                                "stop": 193.28,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "As relevant here, Title VII provides that an employer may not take -- number one, take an adverse action; two, because of; three, an employee\u0027s religion, which includes all aspects of religious observance and practice, unless an employer demonstrates that he is unable to reasonably accommodate to a religious observance or practice."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 193.28,
                                "stop": 196.579,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "The keywords in this case are \u0022because of.\u0022"
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 196.579,
                                "stop": 211.593,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "They typically in part, but for causation, but Title VII expressly relaxes this standard to include situations where a protected characteristic is a \u201cmotivating factor.\u201d"
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 211.593,
                                "stop": 220.75,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "An employee\u0027s actual religious practice may not be a motivating factor in an employer\u0027s adverse employment decision."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 220.75,
                                "stop": 236.644,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Abercrombie asks that we accept as a condition of liability that the employer have actual knowledge of the need for an accommodation, but the statute does not provide for a knowledge requirement, and we lack the power to engraft one."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 236.644,
                                "stop": 248.69,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Title VII forbids adverse employment decisions made with a forbidden motive, whether this motive derives from actual knowledge, a well-founded suspicion, or merely a hunch."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 248.69,
                                "stop": 262.568,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "We are not presented here with the question whether Title VII imposes liability where an employer has no idea that the practice or suspected practice is a religious one, and we do not decide that question."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 262.568,
                                "stop": 267.661,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Here the employer at least suspected that the practice was a religious one."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 267.661,
                                "stop": 276.465,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Its refusal to hire was therefore motivated by the desire to avoid accommodating that practice and that is enough."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 276.465,
                                "stop": 289.69,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "While sure knowledge of a religious practice or an actual request for accommodation may make it easier to infer a prohibited motive, neither is a necessary condition of liability."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 289.69,
                                "stop": 293.834,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Justice Alito has filed an opinion concurring in the judgment."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 293.834,
                                "stop": 301.272,
                                "byte_start": 0,
                                "byte_stop": 0,
                                "text": "Justice Thomas has filed an opinion concurring in part and dissenting in part."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
